{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477419"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:01:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:01:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14513"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14513"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.02,0.04,0.09,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57941"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7208"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17983"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44212"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57941"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of central chest pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The pain varies slightly with respiration and posture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears anxious. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. He has normal heart sounds, no murmur, and no evidence of heart failure. Blood tests reveal a mild leucocytosis and troponin 15 ng/L (\u003C30). An ECG is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Costochondritis","Endocarditis","Myocardial infarction","Myocarditis","Pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Epericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient presents with acute chest pain that varies slightly with respiration and posture, which is characteristic of pericarditis. The ECG finding of widespread ST-segment elevation is also typical of acute pericarditis. The normal troponin level is compatible with uncomplicated pericarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly to pericarditis and may coexist with it. However, the ECG changes of diffuse ST elevation are more typical of pericarditis. Myocarditis typically presents with more non-specific ECG changes or localized ST-T wave abnormalities and would usually cause troponin elevation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely in this young patient without risk factors. While MI can cause ST elevation, the ST elevation would typically be localised to a specific coronary artery territory rather than widespread, and would be associated with troponin elevation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECostochondritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes chest wall pain that is reproducible on palpation. It would not explain the ECG changes seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, heart murmur, and other systemic symptoms. It would not explain the acute chest pain or ECG changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of chest pain characteristics and ECG findings is most consistent with acute pericarditis. Further evaluation, including echocardiography, would be helpful to confirm the diagnosis and rule out complications such as pericardial effusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute pericarditis typically presents with chest pain that varies with respiration and posture, and diffuse ST-segment elevation on ECG.","A normal troponin level does not exclude pericarditis.","Myocarditis and pericarditis can coexist, termed myopericarditis."],"references":["James Heilman, MD, CC BY-SA 3.0. Wikimedia Commons [online]. Available at: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0","Ismail TF. Acute pericarditis: Update on diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2020 Jan;20(1):48-51. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6964178/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14513"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21102"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21102"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8cXTEauuFdlqy18kvPBoNX5i6s4afi.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8cXTEauuFdlqy18kvPBoNX5i6s4afi.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":722}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43400"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T12:55:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-30T08:38:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7208"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57941"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id"